Translator's Note=20


MEIN KAMPF is written in the style of a self-educated mod=C2=AC=20
ern South German with a gift for oratory. Of course this picture=20
does not begin to characterize Hitler the man, but it does, I think,=20
account for the elements of his style.=20

Beginning in his Vienna period, Hitler was a voracious news=C2=AC=20
paper reader. The style of the Austrian press, as Karl Kraus=20
never wearied of pointing out, was slovenly, illogical, pretentious.=20
Even the grammar, doubtless because of the large number of=20
Czechs, Hungarians, and other foreigners in the trade, was un=C2=AC=20
commonly bad. Hitler inveighed against the Viennese melting=20
pot, but was unconsciously influenced by its literary style.=20

He must also have read popular pamphlets on history, psy=C2=AC=20
chology, racist biology, and political subjects. He never at=C2=AC=20
tempted to systematize his knowledge; he retained, for the most=20
part, disjointed facts that met some personal need, and phrases=20
that appealed to his oratorical sense. But the main source of=20
his pet phrases was the theater and the opera. He is full of popu=C2=AC=20
lar quotations from Goethe and Schiller, and largely unintelligible=20
flights of Wagnerian terminology. There is no indication that he=20
ever read any of the German, let alone foreign classics, from=20
which he might have gathered some feeling for stylistic prin=C2=AC=20
ciples.=20

Hitler has been called a paranoiac; at all events, his view of=20
the world is highly personal. Even where he is discussing theo=C2=AC=20
retical matters like =E2=80=98the state/ =E2=80=98race/ etc., he seldom pur=
sues any=20
logic inherent in the subject matter. He makes the most extraor=C2=AC=20
dinary allegations without so much as an attempt to prove them.=20
Often there is no visible connection between one paragraph and=20


Xll=20


