the next. The logic is purely psychological: Hitler is fighting his=20
persecutors, magnifying his person, creating a dream-world in=20
which he can be an important figure. In more concrete passages=20
he is combating political adversaries in his own movement, but=20
even here the continuity is mystifying, because he never tells us=20
whom he is arguing against, but sets up every political expedient=20
as a universal principle.=20

This personalism makes Hitler a poor observer. His style is=20
without color and movement. Images are rare, and when they=20
do appear, they tend to be purely verbal and impossible to=20
visualize, like the =E2=80=98cornerstone for the end of German domina=C2=AC=
=20
tion in the monarchy/ or forcing =E2=80=98the less strong and less healthy=
=20
back into the womb of the eternal unknown.=E2=80=99 The mixed meta=C2=AC=20
phor is almost a specialty of modern German journalism, but=20
Hitler, with his eyes closed to the visual world, was an expert in=20
his own right. Pohner, for example, was =E2=80=98a thorn in the eyes of=20
venal officials.=E2=80=99=20

A non-German of Hitler=E2=80=99s intellectual level would in some=20
ways write quite differently. Germany was a land of high general=20
culture, with the largest reading public of any country in the=20
world. In the lower middle class, there was a tremendous educa=C2=AC=20
tional urge. People who in other countries would read light=20
novels and popular magazines devoured works on art, science,=20
